Eid al Adha celebration is always related to immolation of cows, goat, or lamb. Many people who are financially wealthy buy animals, so they can sacrifice it on the day. The wealthier they are, more animals they buy. On the other side, there are people who are not so wealthy, who doesn't have the money to sacrifice an animal. Sometimes we think that to sacrifice something on Eid al Adha, we need to have money first. But it's not fully true. Sacrificing is not always about money, but the essence of it is giving something we have for the well-being of other people. If we doesn't have money, for example, we can give our time. If we truly want to give back to society, there is no need to have money in the first place. Because a man's true wealth is the good he does in this world. There are many good things we can do without any money. Have a blessed Eid al Adha, everyone!

Hari ini Indonesia memperingati hari kemerdekaannya yang ke-72. Melalui peristiwa proklamasi ini, kita belajar bahwa sebuah tujuan yang besar perlu banyak tangan-tangan kecil dalam eksekusinya. Mulai dari Ibu Fatmawati yang menjahit bendera pusaka, Laksamana Maeda yang meminjamkan rumahnya, Bapak Sayuti Melik yang mengetik naskahnya, juga banyak orang lain yang tidak dapat disebutkan satu persatu. Kita belajar bahwa di atas segala perbedaan, yang terpenting adalah memiliki visi yang sama, dan mau bersatu demi visi tersebut. Semoga melalui teladan para pendiri bangsa, kita menjadi generasi penerus yang melihat perbedaan bukan sebagai penghambat, melainkan sebagai kekayaan. Dirgahayu Indonesia! ✊
...
Today, Indonesia celebrated its' 72nd Independence Day Commemoration. Through this proclamation event, we learn that a great goal needs a lot of little helping hands in the execution. Starting from Mrs. Fatmawati who sewed the flag, Admiral Maeda who lent his house, Mr. Sayuti Melik who typed the proclamation script, and many people that can't be mentioned one by one. We learn that above all differences, the most important thing is to have a same vision, and the willing to unite for it. Hopefully through our founding fathers' sacrifice, we become a successor generation who sees difference not as inhibitor, but as power. Happy independence day, Indonesia! ✊
.

Here is the initial packaging design for 'Lapis Borneo', a brand that sells a cake consists of 3 layers : Surabaya layer cake, traditional layer cake, and brownies as the bottom layer. There are two sizes of the packagings. The owner used these packagings before she printed the real version. We matched the design with the logo, and put the transparent part, so that the three layers of the cake can be shown from outside. We were trusted to produce the packaging, and also printed label stickers and tags to introduce different flavors, and used gold ribbon as an accent. The owner was joining the local woman entrepreneurship competition in Tarakan using this initial packaging design, and she won that competition as the first winner. She hopes that her cake creation can be North Borneo's local souvenir for businessmen and tourists. The new version of the packaging design will be uploaded soon! The cake was also covered by local media. After one full month of Ramadan, here comes the glorious day, Eid ul Fitr. In Indonesia, there are many local tradition that we usually do on Eid ul Fitr. One of the most popular gesture during the day is "sungkem". The tradition came from Javanese people, historically from Surakarta Palace. When the Eid day comes, children and young people sincerely kneeling and kissing the hands of the parent and elder relatives, asking for forgiveness. It is not a shape of worshipping another human, but an act of full respect and politeness to elder people. ‘Lapis Borneo’ (means Borneo layer cake) is a cake brand in Tarakan, North Borneo. The owner used to sell various kinds of cakes, but now she is focusing on one of their signature cake, Borneo layer cake. It’s a cake that consist of 3 layers : Surabaya layer cake, traditional layer cake, and brownies as the bottom layer. Each layers has different meaning. The top layer, that is Surabaya layer cake represents palm oil as the local commodity of Tarakan. The middle layer, that is traditonal layer cake represents the abundance of wood resources there. While the dark brown brownies represents the natural wealth of coal that is the local commodity of Tarakan as well.
The owner was joining the local woman entrepreneurship competition in Tarakan using this logo design. And she won that competition as the first winner. We’re so glad and proud to hear that good news!

Security holograms are labels with a hologram printed onto it for sale security reasons. Security holograms are difficult to forge because they are replicated from a master hologram which requires expensive, specialized and technologically advanced equipment. These types of stickers are often used on documents, collectibles, ID cards, retail goods, for brand authenticity and other important assets. One of the most common type of security hologram is 2D/3D hologram image. This type of "hologram" consists of two or more images stacked in such a way that each is alternately visible depending upon the angle of perspective of the viewer. These holograms display a unique multilevel, multi-colour effect. Research shows that consumers perceive a higher value for products with holograms. If you want your products to look valuable and attractive, these products can truly add a new level of sophistication.⁠⁠⁠⁠

* Promote a goods-selling businesses such as a used car lot discount store or a service business such as a restaurant or massage parlour.
* Persuade people about a social, religious, or political message, as in evangelism or political campaign activities on behalf of a political party or candidate during an election.
* Recruit members for organizations or companies.

Flyers are a great way to build people awareness for any events and promotions. Designing a flyer that's both attractive and easy to read can be a bit tricky.

A wedding invitation is a formal request for someone to be present or participate a wedding. In the middle ages, an invitation only sent among the nobility, since illiteracy was widespread. Historically, wedding invitations were hand-written, made this impractical. Since the printing press technology was invited, nowadays commercial wedding invitations are typically printed using one of the following methods: offset printing, engraving, lithography, thermography, letterpress printing, sometimes blind embossing. Etiquette regarding the text on a formal wedding invitation varies according to country, culture, and language. In Western countries, a formal invitation is typically written in formal, third-person language, saying that the hosts wish for the recipient to attend the wedding and giving its date, time, and place.

Vesak Day celebrates the life of Siddharta Gautama. He was born rich, a royal boy. He was known very smart too. But instead of being lured by wealth, he made a very big decision. He left all he had, to search for the true happiness. He learned from the very best teachers,but ultimately found his own way to happiness. He was enlightened. His enlightment was passed through his students, orally at first, written then. He inspired a lot of people and became the founder of Buddhism. Sometimes in life,we become greedy of our knowledge, our money, our power, our possesions. We don't want to share it to other people. We think that we deserves all we have. It is true, but if we learn from Siddharta Gautama, he didn't become lacking by giving everything he had. On the other side, he gets a lot more. He become very inspiring to many people for a very long time, even long after his death. So don't be afraid to give happiness to other people,because you'll earn more happiness by doing it. A tote bag is a large and often unfastened bag with parallel handles that emerge from the sides of its pouch. It’s usually made of fabric such as canvas, ‘blacu’, or spunbond. Recently, tote bags have been a good idea for a brand’s promotional tools. As people walk the streets, they carry your message in large visible print so others can see. When a business contact continues to use a tote bag you've supplied beyond its initial use, it becomes a personal endorsement which is the best sort of advertising you can get.

Rather than disposable items, good quality promotional tote bags can be re-used over and over, adding an eco friendly slant to your brand image. A printed tote bag is not only a simple solution to the problem of keeping documents and marketing materials together, but also it can be a long-term brand investment.

Easter is about unconditional love. 
A love that always give, with no intention of getting it back. In our daily life, we tend to love selfishly. We often look for love only to fulfill our need. But the truest form of love, contains these things. The first one is appreciation. We love someone because of his/her good features, such as kindness, pretty face, compassion, etc. The second one, which is as important as the first one, is acceptance. People do have two sides. It is easy to love a person in his/her best version, but we have to realize that they have flaws as well. After all, we're all humans. To love someone means to accept that sometimes he/she can annoy us too, yet it doesn't change our feeling towards him/her. With this two things in mind, we can learn to love more selflessly. Have a peaceful Easter, everyone!

A form is a document with spaces (also named fields or placeholders) in which to write or select. Forms may be filled out in duplicate (or triplicate, meaning three times) when the information gathered on the form needs to be distributed to several departments within an organization. This can be done using carbon paper. The form can also include a signature field to allow someone to take responsibility for the accuracy of the information provided.

Red envelopes or angpaos are gifts usually presented at Chinese New Year, given by married couples to children and single people. The red color of the envelope symbolizes good luck and is a symbol to ward off evil spirits. Originated during the Qin Dinasty, the elderly would thread coins with a red string. The money was referred to as "money warding off evil spirits" and was believed to protect the person of younger generation from sickness and death. It was replaced by red envelopes when printing presses became more common. Nowadays, people get used to pack money bills to the envelope, so that the children can't guess the amount of money inside. If you're single, we hope you get a lot of red envelopes. And if you're married, we hope you have a year full of prosperity and happiness among your family! Happy Chinese New Year!

caption.text:
One important highlight in Christmas is about child birth. When a baby is born, many people will come to celebrate his/her birth. They will visit the baby in the hospital, pampering him/her with gifts, many will also ask the mom about her birth experience. But a lot of people forget about the father figure. A lot of people focused only on the baby and the mother. A father, eventhough he's not pregnant, has been giving a lot since a child is concieved. He gave full attention, time, money, and made sure everything's okay for the wellness of his wife and unborn child. He may not get the spotlight, but he's happy just to see his baby arrived safely in his world, and his wife is healthy. May this Christmas bring us a lesson, that we don't have to be the spotlight. That eventhough we are the people behind the scene, we have just as important role as the people on the spotlight. Let's learn to be more humble everyday. Merry Christmas!

Melly Kiong is an Indonesian author and working mother who wrote "Siapa Bilang Ibu Bekerja Tidak Bisa Mendidik Anak dengan Baik" (Who Says That Working Mom Can't Educate Children Well), "Cara Kreatif Mendidik Anak" (Creative Ways to Educate Children) and "Guru-guru Kecil Melly Kiong" (Melly Kiong's Little Teachers), which gets an award from MURI (Indonesian Museum of Record). She wrote all her books according to her personal experience about family life and parenting. In this book called "Horeee, Anakku Sudah Remaja!" (Hoorayy, My Sons Have Become Teenagers!), she wanted to share her dynamic experience in raising two teenager sons, Julian and Matthew, each in different phase of growth.

The book consists of 124 pages, all designed and illustrated in 2 colors, black and orange. The illustration consists of ten key scenes from different chapters of the books, mainly shows the character of Melly, her husband, and her two boys. Each chapter is also designed with note space, so the reader can conclude their own experience after trying Melly's suggestion for each problem that related to the chapter. Beside the inner pages, we also designed the cover. The book was published in 2015, with design adjustment from the publisher.

Eid al Adha celebration is always related to immolation of cows, goat, or lamb. Many people who are financially wealthy buy animals, so they can sacrifice it on the day. The wealthier they are, more animals they buy. On the other side, there are people who are not so wealthy, who doesn't have the money to sacrifice an animal. Sometimes we think that to sacrifice something on Eid al Adha, we need to have money first. But it's not fully true. Sacrificing is not always about money, but the essence of it is giving something we have for the well-being of other people. If we doesn't have money, for example, we can give our time. If we truly want to give back to society, there is no need to have money in the first place. Because a man's true wealth is the good he does in this world. There are many good things we can do without any money. Have a blessed Eid al Adha, everyone!

Tahun ini, Indonesia merayakan peringatan Hari Kemerdekaan yang ke-71. Salah satu figur demokrasi Indonesia, perdana menteri Indonesia termuda, Sutan Sjahrir, pernah berkata: "Kemerdekaan nasional bukanlah pencapaian akhir, namun rakyat yang bebas berkarya adalah pencapaian puncaknya." Pada masa sekarang ini, banyak kesempatan yang tersedia di luar sana. Melalui dunia digital, semua pintu terbuka, semua kemungkinan muncul. Kita memiliki lebih banyak pilihan dibandingkan dengan Sutan Sjahrir semasa hidupnya, namun pemikiran beliau masih relevan hingga sekarang. Dengan pilihan-pilihan yang luas itu, kita seharusnya bersyukur, karena kita bisa bekerja dengan jauh lebih baik, dibandingkan dengan beliau dulu. Sekarang waktunya kita untuk bekerja lebih baik untuk diri kita, keluarga kita, dan pada akhirnya, negara kita, seperti slogan nasional kita tahun ini: "Kerja Nyata". Mari bekerja bersungguh-sungguh untuk Indonesia yang lebih baik!
. . . 
This year, Indonesia celebrates its 71st Independence Day Commemoration. One of Indonesia's democratic figure, the youngest prime minister, Sutan Sjahrir, once said: "National independence is not the final accomplishment, but the peak accomplishment is when people are free to work." These days, there are lots of opportunities provided outside. Through the digital world, every door opens, every possibilities rise up. We have more options than Sutan Sjahrir ever did, yet his thoughts are still relevant until now. With that wide options, we should be grateful, because we can work much better today, than he did many years ago. So it's our chance to act and work better for ourselves, our family, and in the end, for our country, as our national slogan this year: "Kerja Nyata" (Real Work). Let's work for real for better Indonesia!

caption.text:
Eid al Fitr celebration in Indonesia is related with 'mudik' tradition. The happiness that awaits us when we meet our family and friends in hometown. Along the way, there will always be some obstacles: real bad traffic, for example. But the obstacle won't prohibit us to be happy. Happiness comes from the little things. Just enjoy the traffic. We can listen and sing along to music, have a quality chat with our travel partners, meeting random people in gas station, opening our car window so we can talk to other driver, etc. In the end, the process matters too. If we enjoy the ride, we will reach our hometown happier too. Have a blessed Eid, everyone! Eat a lot of ketupat and opor in your hometown!

caption.text:
Just as the tale of Prince Siddharta, his life story represents 3 important meanings, which are the birth, the achievement of perfect enlightenment, and Parinibbana achievement.

The birth is not literally means as a baby's arrival in the world, but also simbolizes the birth of a new persona, leaving the bad one behind. A person should continually change and develop his/herself to be better day by day.

When we wake up everyday, it is our "moment of life", because we can still open our eyes and breath. We should cherish it. A day wasted will decrease our chances in many things. There's also a sayings that everyday we wake up, our life lessens a day. So let's wake up and achieve positive things everyday.

Happy Vesak Day, Sabbe Satta Bhavantu Sukhitatta, may all beings be happy 😊

When Kartini first wrote a letter to her Dutch pen pals, she wouldn't have realized that her thought would have such a great impact to Indonesian society. She was just a young woman who expressed her dislike to be dictated by aristocracy culture. But unlike other women around her, she moved. She tried her best to change the status quo, that women was always considered as "number two people" in society. She questioned everything. Maybe it looked wild and too radical at that time, but now, she became a great inspiration for us. It is our time to continue what Kartini had started a hundred years ago. It's okay to be 'wild' at times, if what we pursue is not wrong. Even if we didn't make it, we won't know if our acts, our works, our thoughts, someday be an inspiration to someone. Don't stop pursuing anything we want to do, just because society disagree with us. In the end, it is our life, not theirs. Happy Kartini's Day to all Indonesian women!

Be optimistic to believe that there will always be a better ending, if we have the courage to begin again. Happy Easter!

caption.text: The Day of Silence (Nyepi) is a day before Hindu people celebrated Caka new year. It is a quite day to reflect, that consists of four main rituals: amati geni (not using fire or lights), amati karya (not working), amati lelungan (not traveling), and amati lelanguan (not having entertainment). For some people, they add more rituals, like fasting or not speaking during the day. All of these are done, so that Hindu people can be ready to start new year with a pure heart. My favorite thing in New Year's Eve is definitely the fireworks. And it makes me reflect, that people are like fireworks. Fireworks are beautiful when they vary in colors. We have different personalities, different backgrounds, races, you name it. And through that differences, we still manage to unite in one world and be very beautiful in some way. A firework sparks in a short amount of time. The same works for people too. Sometimes, a person come to our life and leave in a sudden. We also have limited time to live. So make sure in our moment, we spark the best we can! This is our last post in 2015, we hope you have a great year ahead! Happy New Year!

This is a folder design and printing for Kantor Pelayanan Pajak (KPP) Pratama Subang, a Tax Service Office at Subang - one of West Java's regency. They have a motto: "Be like a pineapple. Stand up straight, put on crown. Be sweet inside." So we put pineapple illustration together with that motto on the cover. They wanted a folder that wraps two books and a CD inside. They also wanted a 'surprise' effect when someone opens it, so we made the proposals and CD hidden.

Personally, I had seen Eid ul Adha celebration several times. About one or two times, it was held in front of my house. What I remembered the most, is that the 'qurban' cried before the sacrification. At the time, I didn't know why the animal shed tears, but I heard from the elders that animals can sense about their fate of death. I am always full of emotions everytime I see a 'qurban' cried, and I wonder, where will their souls go after the sacrifice process? I finally get an answer. Muslims believe that with sacrificing animals, when they died, the 'qurban' will be their ride to afterlife. So the animals didn't die for nothing; they will have a major part to escort people to Heaven. I am really relieved that I have an answer for this long-time question of mine. Eid Mubarak, everyone!

'Ayo kerja' or 'let's work' in English is the name for national movement announced by Indonesian President, Mr. Joko Widodo (Jokowi) on March 10th, 2015. It's also used as Indonesian 70th Independence Day Commemoration slogan. He said that 'let's work' is a practical realization of thinking revolution, mindset revolution, character revolution, and also mental revolution that become the responsibility of citizens and government to make Indonesia a better country. Yes my friend, a leader alone, however great he is, can't change a very big nation. We as citizens have the same responsibility to realize our vision of a better Indonesia, starting from ourselves. Finally the day is coming! The Eid ul-Fitr celebration is always appealing from many sides. But this time I'm interested to find out more about one of Eid ul-Fitr special dish, 'ketupat'. Suddenly it crossed my mind : Why there must be 'ketupat' to complete Eid ul-Fitr celebration here in Indonesia? Is there any special meanings or philosophy behind that? After browsing for a while, I found sooo many meanings apparently. I've never thought about any philosophy of 'ketupat' before besides its yummy taste 😋 Actually, in Javanese, 'ketupat', which is also known as 'kupat', is the acronym of 'ngaku lepat' (means 'ngaku salah' in Indonesian or 'confessing mistakes' in English), which is harmonious with the essence of Eid ul Fitr. While 'janur' leaf that is used to wrap the 'ketupat' is the acronym of 'jatining nur' (means 'hati nurani' in Indonesian or 'conscience' in English). 'Janur' leaves are overlappingly braided, represents human's life that is not always smooth. There are a lot of troubles, big or small, that make human do mistakes, consciously or not. It is also braided endlessly, as a symbol that we have to continuously maintain our relationship with family, relatives, and society, despite of social status, religion, or race. 'Ketupat' is loaded with rice, as a symbol of human's gluttony, because rice is Indonesian main dish. So the philosophy of 'ketupat' is human's lust, greed, and gluttony, that is wrapped in conscience. It is our job to keep ourselves from bad desires and train our own consciousness.

After confessing mistakes and asking for forgiveness from each other, Eid ul-Fitr celebration is completed with a feast. When the 'ketupat' is opened, the rice inside becomes visible, represents a clean and holy heart that has already confessed its mistakes and wants to start over.

This philosophy is taught by Sunan Kalijaga, one of the Wali Songo : nine biggest Islam theologicians in Java. After I learnt about it, now I don't see 'ketupat' on the same way like before. I hope it can inspire you too. Have a blessed Eid ul-Fitr everyone! 😊 #hariraya #idulfitri #idulfitri1436h #eidulfitr #eidmubarak #greeting #ketupat #desaingrafis #graphicdesign

caption.text: Vesak Day celebrates the life of Siddharta Gautama. He was born rich,a royal boy. He was known very smart too. But instead of being lured by wealth,he made a very big decision. He left all he had,to search for the true happiness. He learned from the very best teachers,but ultimately found his own way to happiness. He was enlightened. His enlightment was passed through his students,orally at first,written then. He inspired a lot of people and became the founder of Buddhism. Sometimes in life,we become greedy of our knowledge,our money,our power,our possesions. We don't want to share it to other people. We think that we deserves all we have. It is true,but if we learn from Siddharta Gautama,he didn't become lacking by giving everything he had. On the other side,he gets a lot more. He become very inspiring to many people for a very long time,even long after his death. So don't be afraid to give happiness to other people,because you'll earn more happiness by doing it. Have a happy Vesak Day,may all beings be happy :) #vesakday #vesak2015 #waisak #buddhism #buddha #gautama #light #candle #happiness #photography #greeting #design #desain #desaingrafis #thehummingbirddesign #jakarta

This year is the second time we design Isra Miraj greeting. Last year we were mesmerized when we read about Isra's and Miraj's history. This year we want to emphasize about one thing: Isra Miraj commemorates a day when Allah told Prophet Mohammad to do five Shalats a day. We learned that the name ISLAM,as far as we know, is also an acronym for five Shalats: Isha, Subuh, Luhur, Azhar, and Maghrib. How beautiful it is,that a religion's name is based on its main prayers. Although I'm not a Muslim, I'm still impressed by how Muslims put praying as a very important daily activity, five times a day. Have a blessed day friends!

Every woman has their own idealism to live as a woman. There are women who are satisfied just by being a good mother for her kids, a good wife for her husband, or a good child for her parents. But there are some other women who feel they can have more roles as they have more values, such as more abilities, skills, authorizations, money, chances, even passions to not just satisfied by walking on any standard roles. They have another 'calling' to be filled. They use their extra values as the tools to actualize themselves, doing anything that can reveal their true selves, working in harmony with their passions, level up their values, and at the higher level of satisfaction, sharing their values and helping others to have a better life.

Here is the link about 6 inspiring women in Indonesia who have uncommon life standards. Take your time to read this link :
http://www.hipwee.com/motivasi/7-wanita-indonesia-yang-layak-kamu-teladani-agar-hidup-tak-melulu-soal-galau-jodoh-dan-materi/

But, as mentioned above, every woman has their own idealism. The decision is in your hand. Just remember to aware of what values you have, be grateful of them, and maximize that values as the tools to live a better life everytime. The thing is, be the best version of yourself!

Nobody's perfect, that makes us human. We make mistakes. Sometimes we make the same mistake twice. Sometimes we make the same mistake over and over again. But remember that we can always start fresh, start new.

Like a quotes said, to live fully is to let go and die with each passing moment, and to be reborn in new one. There's nothing wrong about making mistakes. They usually end up teaching us something valuable. Just make sure we forgive ourselves for making those mistakes, and be the better version of us everyday.

Happy Easter, everyone! :) With love,

Every couple is unique.
Each has their own favorite places to hang out, favorite ways to express their feeling towards each other,
favorite songs to sing along.
Some maybe don't hang out, but prefer a cozy cuddle at home.
Some may express their feelings through words, some through actions.
Some like energetic songs, some only listen to slow instrumentals.
There is no such thing as 'right' or 'wrong' in a relationship between two people.
People may see you as weird, but as long as you two
are comfortable with each other, what do you need more?
You can't please everyone, by the way.
Oh, on this Valentine's Day, you may, or may not celebrate it.
It's up to you!

So Happy Valentine's Day for those who celebrate,

Finally we have reached the last day of 2014. Many memories have been made, and tomorrow we will start a new chapter. One thing that relates with new year is resolution. We often start a new year with new resolutions, new hopes, new dreams to accomplish. But at the same time, we often forget to finish our resolutions for this year. We become too eager to start something new, and left the old ones behind. May we find the wisdom to remember that our old, unfinished resolutions are just as important as the new ones, because finishing is just as important as starting. And a resolution becomes more worthwhile if we finish it. May you all have a great year of accomplishment in 2015! #newyear #greeting #2015 #design #vector #illustration #thehummingbirddesign

Christmas is about the birth of a child. Childbirth is something that almost everyone longing for, a moment of joy, to see the cute baby's face for the first time. But after all the euphoria, we'll start to experience reality. Taking care of a baby turns out not that simple. It needs a lot of time, energy, and commitment. The same thing works for our faith. When Christmas comes, many people are very excited to go to church. But a couple weeks later, that excitement just gone away. Hope we can take care of our faith better this year, be the 'good parent' for it to grow well in our hearts, not only on Christmas, but every single day. Have a warm Christmas, everyone! 😊 #christmas #greeting #cute #illustration #design #vector #thehummingbirddesign

Claudia's Graduation Gift

Graduation is one of the proudest moment in our life. We finally accomplish a degree, after years of learning. Ms. Claudia just got her master degree at Theology, and a dear friend of her asked us to design a memorable gift for her graduation day. At first we didn't know what to make. But after a brainstorming session, we finally decided to make an illustration and very simple papertole with it, equipped with a card and packaging. The illustration itself tells everything about what Ms. Claudia did, do and will do for the rest of her life. Jesus is placed at the center of the picture, as a symbol that her spiritual journey begins and ends in Him. It also reminds Ms. Claudia to put Jesus in the middle of everything. The quotes there, taken from The Bible, also represents her well, because she is still in her 20s, and maybe there are some people who will look down on her as a priest. But we believe youthfulness doesn't always represent lack of wisdom and goodness. We hope that Ms. Claudia will always have a pure heart and a happy soul in worshiping God. Happy graduation! #graduation #gift #papertole #manual #illustration #cute #design #customizedneeds #personal #flower #spiritual #christian #memory #bible #quotes #fororder #jakarta #desain #ilustrasi #jesus #colorpencil #handdrawn

Today our country reaches its 69th year of independence. As our former president, Soekarno said, Indonesia is one of the most beautiful country. We do have very beautiful scenery, very rich in culture too. But sometimes we get distracted by the people. The bad people who let that beauty lost, or disappear, by doing things unresponsibly. In this year, let's be a better citizen. We maybe don't have the capacity to conserve animals or rainforests, but we sure can do small things, as simple as not littering on public streets, or be patient and polite while using public transportation.

Let's make Indonesia proud of us. Let the world see how beautiful Indonesia IS, not remembering how beautiful Indonesia WAS.

Happy 69th Independence Day, Indonesia! ✊😊 #indonesia #independence #independenceday #kemerdekaan #merdeka #merahputih #dirgahayu #69th #17agustus #red #white #indonesian #beautiful #country #soekarno #quotes #iloveindonesia

caption.text:
Eid ul Fitr is a very joyful moment for me, although I'm not a Moslem.
I love the holiday, of course (We have a long Eid ul Fitr holiday here in Indonesia!), but there is another thing that I like the most. When Ramadhan almost over, my neighbors usually visit me and bring ketupat, opor (chicken in coconut milk), rendang, sambal goreng ati (spicy fried potato with beef liver), and other tasty dishes. They share their happiness, togetherness and hospitality with us, despite of our different religion. This "food-giving" culture on feast days have been common for me since I was at young age. My mom and dad also bring nian gao (basket cake) to neighbors' home at Chinese New Years. I'm proud to live at an area where we can have harmony in our diversity.

I hope you all have a joyful heart and full tummy in this Eid ul Fitr! :D

This is the first time we make a post to commemorate Isra' Mi'raj.
At first, we did not really understand what Isra' Mi'raj is. But, for us, it's kinda weird to make something we don't understand. So, we searched the net, trying to understand what Isra' Mi'raj is and we found it interesting.

Isra' Mi'raj is the "name" of two different events. Isra' is the journey of Prophet Muhammad from Al-Masjid Al-Haram to Al-Aqsa Mosque (physical). Mi'raj is the journey of Prophet Muhammad from Al-Aqsa Mosque to the highest heaven (seventh heaven), Sidratul Muntaha (spiritual). The reason why Isra' Mi'raj become important is because it was the time when Prophet Muhammad was ordered directly by Allah to do the Ṣalāt,
five times a day, which is done by all Moslems until now.

Isra' Mi'raj itself is commemorated by Moslems all over the world to maintain their faith. By this fact, regardless of our religious beliefs, this can also be the moment for us to remind ourselves that we have to keep our faith and be strong spiritually.

That's it, we wish the best for all. And may all Moslems' faith be stronger in this Isra' Mi'raj day and on.

In her time, Raden Ajeng Kartini (1879-1904) was unable to get a proper education. Nowadays, because of her, Indonesian women have a lot more freedom than before. We are well-educated, respected by men, free to choose our job, etc. But on the other side, we often forget our role as a woman and misunderstand the true meaning of emancipation. Emancipation is not just about gender equation, it's more about embracing our femininity in every aspects of life, and have balance between our rights and responsibility. #kartini #design #vector #silhouette #april21st #kartiniday #women #emancipation #heroine #indonesia

Do you notice that rabbit appears everywhere when Easter comes?

Why rabbit?

Rabbit symbolizes new life, because it is fertile to have many babies. New life means new hope. Whatever our problems are in life, we will always have one thing, that is 'hope'. As long as we don't lose hope, there must be a way out for our problems, and it will be the spirit for us to get up and start over a better life... So, let hope flourishes our life to be lovely and joyful!

Happy Easter, everyone! :D
